<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT205 Introduction to Law</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course is an introductory course to the general notion of law. The course covers the following topics:
      social life and law; the significance of law; main legal principles and rules of social behaviour; basic
      concepts of the private law; distinction between public law and private law; branches of private law. An
      introductory course focusing on building a theoretical framework towards the analysis of law, and also
      developing the student's vocabulary regarding basic legal concepts and principles. The role of the state and
      of legal institutions. A brief overview of the development of different legal systems along with a survey of
      different branches of the law. During the course, "Law" students are perceived important knowledge: the meaning
      of the Constitution as the fundamental law of the country, the principles and elements of the constitutional
      order of the Kyrgyz Republic, the role and nature of the state and law at the present stage Development Framework
      , the improvement of civil society, political system, the content of the inalienable rights and freedoms of
      citizens and state responsibility for the implementation of political, economic, social and other opportunities
      for the individual, for creating conditions for a dignified life and free development rights. The aim of this
      course is mastery of the students knowledge in basic theory of law, constitutional, civil, family, labor,
      administrative, criminal and environmental law, and civil process to develop respect for law and observance of
      lawful behavior in society. Course objectives are to develop students' understanding of the legal system of the
      Kyrgyz Republic of values and functions of law in the formation of the rule of law, strengthening the rule of law
      in the country, the ability to understand the laws and regulations, enforce laws, make decisions in accordance
      with the law review legislation and practice of its application, to be guided by law and in the literature and
      based on acquired knowledge to solve specific problems arising in practice.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>ELL251 Diplomatic English</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      International relations has in many respects its very own lexicon. There are phrases, expressions used in the
      field which are sui generis. These particular words and specific terms require familiarity and understanding in
      order for them to be comprehensible. Bearing these in mind this course aims to improve the general level of
      English required for the purposes of international relations of all participants. In terms of improvement, the
      course aims to focus on both reading capacity and clear expression in writing. These dual skills will be augmented
      by verbal presentations. What this course does not offer is raising the level of conversational English or grammar
      or widespread knowledge of English literature. Its primary aim is to understand written materials related to
      international relations and to be able to express clearly and concisely in written form matters relating to the
      field of diplomacy and international relations.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
