    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>PHL251 Philosophy I</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The primary object of Political Philosophy is to introduce the undergraduate students in the Department
      of International Relations to theory in political science. The focus of attention is the emergence and
      development of democratic theory in political science. This course examines the history of political
      thought from the ancient Greeks through the medieval period. Theorists read will include Plato, Aristotle,
      Polybius, Cicero, St. Augustine, Aquinas, Dante, Marsilius of Padua. We will read and critically analyze
      their works by asking what key ideas are being expressed, what they tell us about the society in which they
      were written, and how their ideas differ from our own thoughts about politics. Political Philosophy is
      concerned with the fundamental questions of public life. It addresses such issues as the nature of political
      authority, the relationship of the state to the individual, and the obligations and responsibilities that
      citizens owe to one another. Over the last several decades the field of political theory has undergone a
      remarkable revival, with theorists bringing insights from classic texts to bear on present day issues. This
      course offers an introduction to the field by examining a few basic concepts - "authority", "liberty", and
      "justice" - and discussing some of the ways in which these concepts have been employed in discussions of current
      political issues. While some of the readings draw upon "classics" in the field - e.g., Plato, Aristotle, Thomas
      Hobbes, John Locke, David Hume, Thomas Jefferson, James Madison, and John Stuart Mill - we will also look at
      writings by present-day moral philosophers, political theorists, and social commentators and will read a number
      of recent Supreme Court decisions to see what light they cast on different ways of thinking about such issues
      as free speech, privacy rights, and affirmative action.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>PHL252 Philosophy II</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The course explores the different accounts neoliberalism, institutionalism, Marxism, and poststructuralism
      provide of changes in government over the last twenty years, and the different theories that inform these accounts.
      The last twenty years has witnessed a transformation of the public sector in many western industrial democracies.
      This transformation is often described as one from government to governance, from bureaucracy to markets and networks.
      Good governance is now a part of the lending criteria of international bodies such as the World Bank. But what is
      governance? How should we explain its emergence? And what are its implications for public policy and democracy? This
      course examines the ways in which governance is theorized within neoliberalism, institutionalism, Marxism, and
      poststructuralism. With each theory, we begin by looking at the narrative it provides of the origins and workings
      of governance. Thereafter we look at the way in which the narrative embodies theoretical positions on rationality,
      structure and agency, and power, as well as the way in which it suggests normative proposals for public policy and
      democracy. The course also provides students, in small groups, with an opportunity to study changing patterns of
      government in a particular state, such as Australia, Canada, Denmark, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway, or the
      US. The course attempts to promote an awareness of the way in which questions about contemporary governance are
      inextricably linked to various theoretical and normative positions.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>Turkish (TUR251-254, 351-354)</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The purpose of this course is to improve students’ Turkish fluency and accuracy, to help them improve their speaking
      and writing ability.
    </div>
  </div>
