</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT301 History of International Relations I</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The primary object of Political History I is to introduce the students of the Department of International
      Relations to the origins of modern nation-state system and international relations, so that they will get
      familiar with basic concepts such as nationalism, liberalism, imperialism, socialism, armament race, and
      decolonization that have underlied some modern institutions; and with significant developments and events
      such as the French Revolution, Napoleonic Wars, Industrial Revolution, Bolshevik Revolution, World Wars,
      Cold War, and disintegration of the Soviet Union that have shaped modern international system. The course
      surveys the Middle Ages from the eve of the French Revolution to the imperial age in the mid-nineteenth
      century with a special focus on the developments in Central Asian region, and such topics as Tsarist Russian
      expansionism and the emergence of Central Asian nationalities, during the first semester. Among the topics
      covered are the economic and political transformations of the 18th and 19th centuries, the flowering of science
      and industry during this same period, the highlights of European thought from Enlightenment to liberal revolutions,
      and the problems and achievements of the early modern age. Rather than studying the details of political history,
      students focus on the enduring legacy of early modern European society — the great works of art, architecture,
      poetry, political theory, theology,
      and philosophy produced during this formative period in the development of modern Western culture.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT302 History of International Relations II</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Political History II is the continuation of Political History I in the first semester. The course surveys
      the modern age from European colonialism and imperialism to the collapse of the Soviet Union and Post-Cold
      War era. Among the topics covered are the economic and socio-political transformations of the 19th and 20th
      centuries, the flowering of rapid transportation and communication means during this same period, mass
      production and rapid industrialization, motives behind colonization such as white man’s burden and civilizing
      mission or capitalist appetite for raw materials and new markets, shifting balance of power in Europe, colonial
      rivalry, origins of World War One and WWII, post WWII international system, decolonization, Cold War, the end
      of the Cold War, and new international order.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT303 Introduction to International Relations I</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      PThe main purpose of the course is to familiarize students with the basic concepts and a general understanding
      of the international relations discipline. Issues are globalization; main international relations theories;
      realism; liberalism; world-system theory; emergence of the modern international system; the evolution of
      international society; international security in the post-Cold War era; international political economy in an
      age of globalization, etc
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>IINT304 Globalization of World Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This is the continuation and second part of the first term course Introduction to International Relations.
      Accordingly, this course provides a framework for understanding international relations by giving a broad
      introduction to international politics. The main purpose of the course is to familiarize students with the
      basic concepts and a general understanding of the international relations discipline. Diplomacy; environmental
      issues; North-South gap; poverty; gender issues; nationalism; cultural issues; the West and the Rest;
      international governmental and non-governmental organizations; international regimes; nuclear proliferation;
      humanitarian intervention; regionalism and integration; global trade and finance; human rights, etc.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>ECO301 Microeconomics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Introduces the process and analysis of resource allocation in a decentralized market economy. Special
      focus on the coordination of consumer and producer decisions through price adjustments under alternative
      market structures and public policies. Theory of choice: properties of choice, binary choice and preference,
      aggregation of choice: approval voting, voting paradox, aggregation of preferences: Arrow's Theorem, utility
      and preference, revealed preference, demand theory: the demand curve, income and substitution effects,
      consumers' surplus, pure exchange and general equilibrium: Edgeworth's solution, Walras's solution. First
      and Second Welfare Theorems, manipulation of Walrasian solution, production: production sets and production
      functions, cost functions, the competitive firm's demand, imperfect competition:
      equilibrium concepts of Cournot, Stackelberg and Bertrand, simple regulation theory.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>ECO302 Macroeconomics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Introduces the nature and analysis of data and phenomena that impact the national economy.
      Special focus on the problems of inflation, recession, unemployment, international trade and
      financial system instability. Traditional Keynesian and Monetarist views of the economy within
      the context of linear dynamic economic models, introduction to expectational dynamics and "rational
      expectations" models.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT305 Comparative Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course begins with the introduction of basic concepts used by political scientists to analyze
      political phenomena - power, authority, nation, state, political culture, political system, and the like.
      We will then use these concepts to analyze various transitions away from authoritarian government and
      toward democracy. Attention will be given to contemporary transitions (e.g., the Soviet Union, South Africa)
      as well as to the historical cases of democratization in Western Europe. This course sets out to introduce
      students to the elements of comparative analysis by examining great political currents in the modern age.
      It will begin with lectures on "pre-modern" political systems, then proceed to examine the following subjects:
      1) the economic and technological revolutions of the modern age, the rise of western global hegemony and the
      institutions of the liberal democratic state; 2) challenges to these institutions and hegemony: fascism,
      national socialism, communism (in Russia and China); 3) the "end of the cold war" and attempts to create a
      new world order based on democratic institutions and open markets; 4) a variety of responses to these attempts
      (developmental, revolutionary, populist-fundamentalist, post-modern.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT307 Constitutional Law</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      In this seminar, we explore a set of widely held assumptions called constitutionalism, and examine
      alternatives for creating, enacting, and substituting constitutions in writing. Several modern
      constitution-making efforts around the world are analyzed, with a view toward identifying tools
      or norms of universal applicability. Does a bill of rights garner for individual rights any greater
      state deference? How should regulatory powers be dispersed in federal systems? When should representation
      supplant direct government? How can change be accommodated without injury to stability? How is the rule
      of law guaranteed in a democratic republic? A study of the basis of the constitutional system and governmental
      authorities of the Kyrgyz Republic.Moreover , a study of the rights, freedoms, honor and dignity of the
      citizens of the Kyrgyz Republic. Social issues related to the constitutional system are examined in depth
      . Not only theoretical issues will be discussed, but also practical implementations will be introduced.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>MAN241 Introduction to Business</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Introductory class on Management Theory. The lecture gives theoretical foundation and current issue
      on the basic topics of management. The lecture refers to the related economic theories although it mainly
      emphasizes on the firm specific factor. An introductory survey of the business world, government and society;
      basic business functions and their interrelationships; production, finance, marketing, research and development;
      introduction to management functions; organization.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>MAN341 Accounting</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Introduction to basic concepts and principles of accounting; recording business transactions and year
      end adjustments, preparation of trial balance, balance sheet and income statement; opening and closing
      the accounts; detail analysis of major accounts: cash, receivables, inventory (including inventory
      valuation methods), fixed assets, current liabilities and capital accounts; going public raising capital;
      retained earnings and reserve accounts.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>MAN351 Statistics I</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The course addresses an intoroductory statistics including descriptive statistics, random variables,
      distribution theory, estimation theory and hypothesis testing. The prerequisite subjects are linear
      mathematics and calculus of the first year undergraduate level. Probability theory covering permutations,
      combinations, finite sample spaces; conditional probability, random variables, functions of random variables,
      moments, moment generating function, theoretical distributions, joint distributions.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>MAN352 Statistics II</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Elements of statistical analysis; statistical inference including estimation and tests: hypotheses;
      introduction to time-series analysis; analysis of variance, correlation; regression.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT304 Political Processes in Kyrgyzstan & Globalization</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The purpose of this course is to analyze politics in Kyrgyzstan. The main topics are political development
      in Kyrgyzstan; historical background; freedom and authority; governmental institutions; political parties;
      civil society; non-governmental organizations; politics and media; politics and religion; nation-building
      and state-building process; post-communist politics, etc.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT308 International Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course introduces the study of international politics. It begins with the traditional problems that
      shaped the contemporary field of international relations (war and peace, poverty and prosperity among states)
      and goes on to consider what it means to build social science theories that try to explain them. Students will
      become familiar with some of the major IR theories and then apply them to historical case studies. Topics include:
      the development of European states and their relations in the 19th Century; World War I and the Great Depression;
      World War II and the origins of the Cold War; the "American Decade" in international political economy; crisis
      and détente; the diffusion of power during the 1970s; North-South relations; the trends toward multilateralism
      during the 1980s; the end of the Cold War; and the effects of technological change, globalization and U.S.
      prosperity on international politics in the 1990s. At the end of the course we will discuss how the events of
      September 2001 might affect current thinking about international relations and the future of the state system.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT310 Law of Diplomacy</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The course covers major chapters of public international law, although it can not touch upon all the
      topics of a standard manual. Specific emphasis is given to the rights of the individual, (human rights,
      refugee law), the rules of international transactions (law of treaties, diplomacy), the settlement of disputes
      (responsibility, methods, ICJ) and the law of natural resources (sea, outer space, freshwaters). Although the
      approach is mainstream and aims at presenting law as it is applied by the international subjects and tribunals,
      critical thoughts will repeatedly penetrate discussions. The reader reflects the diversity of international
      legal writing: it contains chapters from major textbooks, articles from leading European and US journals, and
      primary sources.The course is based on mixed teaching techniques, the dominant element being discussions based
      on readings and on knowledge derived from other disciplines.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT401 Theory of International Relations</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Theories of International Relations: An introduction to the theory and practice of International Relations for
      the professional degree students in the MA in International Relations Program at the Maxwell School of Syracuse
      University. The course is a survey and critique of approaches to understanding international relations from the
      perspective of the practitioner who must deal with problems of individual choice, small groups, and organizational
      factors in the conduct of International Relations.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT403 Current Kyrgyz Foreign Policy</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The purpose of this course is to analyze formulation of Kyrgyz foreign policy in international and regional
      context. The course will focus on such topics as determinants and variables of Kyrgyz foreign policy; a
      historical background; the relations between Kyrgyzstan and the other countries in the region or throughout
      the world, etc.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT405 Diplomacy I</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Conventional wisdom has it that that war begins where diplomacy ends. Any war in this day and age of
      modern weapons can only bring about mass destruction and untold misery. It is self-evident, therefore,
      that we need to closely study the art and craft of diplomacy not only as a means of conduct of relations
      between nations but also as an instrument of peace, its origins, practice and limitations and how it has
      helped mankind in the course of its societal evolution. Diplomacy being as old as history itself, this course
      will attempt to analyze the history, theory and practice of diplomacy from the time of the Greek city states
      and the Roman empire, through Machiavelli, Grotius, to the modern times of Kissinger. Main topics to be covered
      during this semester are meaning and scope of diplomacy; phases in the evolution of diplomacy (traditional,
      new, Cold War, etc.); diplomacy as a communication and negotiation process and as a foreign policy instrument;
      public diplomacy; summit diplomacy; functions of diplomats; rules of effective diplomacy; theory of diplomacy;
      conference diplomacy; and future of diplomacy.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT406 Diplomacy II</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Conventional wisdom has it that that war begins where diplomacy ends. Any war in this day and age of modern weapons can only bring about mass destruction and untold misery. It is self-evident, therefore, that we need to closely study the art and craft of diplomacy not only as a means of conduct of relations between nations but also as an instrument of peace, its origins, practice and limitations and how it has helped mankind in the course of its societal evolution. Diplomacy being as old as history itself, this course will attempt to analyze the history, theory and practice of diplomacy from the time of the Greek city states and the Roman empire, through Machiavelli, Grotius, to the modern times of Kissinger. Main topics to be covered during this semester are goals and means of foreign policy; diplomatic etiquette; the formulation of foreign policy objectives; foreign policy decision making process; foreign policy actions; diplomatic bargaining; instruments of policy; explanations of foreign policy outputs, etc.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT407 Middle Eastern Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course is an advanced introduction to the comparative politics of the Middle East and North Africa. It makes an effort to explain the sources of instability and violence in the region, focusing on the process of state-building and state disintegration. It examines, in comparative context, the particular experiences of Middle Eastern countries to answer questions concerning the nature of regimes, nationalism and institutional change. In doing so it links case studies to the rich theoretical literature on political development in the Third World and reviews the domestic, regional and international factors that have shaped the political landscape of the region. This is not a course on the Arab-Israeli conflict. The approach is thematic, not chronological. Nevertheless, the course begins with a broad historical overview of the region, covering the legacies of the Ottoman Empire, European colonialism and the Mandate period. Other topics include the sources of instability and revolutionary movements, conflicts between Pan Arabism, nationalism and Pan Islamism, the emergence of revolutionary regimes and monarchies, Islamic fundamentalism, and the particularly difficult processes of state-building and national integration in the heterogeneous societies of the region. The course ends by considering the case of the most recent Gulf war as a conflict in which all these forces were at work.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>ECO441 International Economics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course is an introduction to theories and issues in international political economy. Our emphasis will be on understanding bargaining between rich and poor countries. In particular, we will examine the political and economic conditions conducive to the development of cooperative international economic behavior among countries. The first part of the course will consider three analytical approaches to interpret economic interaction among countries - liberalism, dependency, and mercantilism. This part of the course also will consider theories used to explain the evolution of international arrangements - regimes - in the international system. The second part of the course will focus on four issue areas of key significance for North-South relations: trade, money, multinationals, and commodities. Our emphasis will be on the post-World War II transformation of rules and behavior in these issue-areas. The third and concluding part of the course will review the theoretical ideas and examine the prospects of the less-developed countries in the international system and the future of international economic cooperation. A background in international relations, international economics, or post-World War II history will be an advantage.
    </div>
  </div>
