<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT411 International Law I</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      Undergraduate lecture course with discussion groups. This is a course on the role of public international law for students of political science. The focus is on what role law plays in the design and implementation of foreign policies, as well as international politics more generally. Topics that will be offered include sovereignty, treaties, and rules regarding the use of force. We will also cover areas of contemporary concern such as international terrorism, human rights, international environmental accords, and international economic law and institutions, such as those embodied in the World Trade Organization. While attention will be paid to legal doctrine and argumentation, this course will focus on the relationship between international law and international politics more generally.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT American Foreign Policy</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course offers an overview of key events that have shaped America’s foreign policy from the Revolutionary period to the present day. It also explores America’s strategic and ideological commitments that have shaped these events. Themes examined include America’s universalistic aspirations, its liberal and realist strains of thought, and its role as nation-builder with developing countries. The Cold War, the War on Terror, and modern-day trade policy furnish extensive case studies through which to explore these themes.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT402 International Organizations</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course intends to examine the evaluation of international organizations in relation to the developments in the international system. A short history of the various pacts and systems until the foundation of the league of Nations will be studied in comparison with the League of Nations and the united Nations system. The focus of this course will be generally on the international organizations of the post-war international system. NATO, the Warsaw Pact, the Arab League, the Non-Alignment movement, etc. are to be discussed from the point of political developments between East and West and North and South.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT404 Regional Integration & European Union</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The European Union (with its 15 member states and a population of more than 370 million) has become an increasingly powerful actor in regional and global affairs and is a major factor in the emergent "new Europe". Against this background, this course sets out to introduce students to the institutional arrangements and decision-making processes in the EU. In doing so, it also serves as an introduction to comparative politics and the analysis of public policy-making. Having looked at the historical development of European integration and theoretical approaches to the study of the EU as a political system in the first part of the course, we will move on to analyze the institutions of EU government. Finally, we will shift attention towards substantive EU-policies and cover key policy developments within the EU in recent years.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT408 Third World Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This lecture course exposes students to the main debates in the field of economic and political development and underdevelopment. It covers the classic texts and scholarly traditions in the field and also gives students a sense of the frontiers of research on the political economy of development, focusing especially on the changing nature of the international economy and its impact on domestic and local economies. Although the emphasis is on arguments and analytical constructs, students will also be exposed to case material from Latin America, Asia and Africa. “Third World” includes less developed or underdeveloped countries in Africa, Latin America, and Asia. However, the course will also refer to the developing countries, which cannot be regarded as either developed or less developed. This course deals with socioeconomic and political problems of developing or "Third World" countries. Required readings focus initially on topics such as the nature of underdevelopment, the legacy of indigenous cultural traditions and divisions, the legacies of colonialism and the impact of exploitation, all emanating from more developed countries, and, then, on the problems and prospects of the development models and strategies to which developing countries have been subjected by their own authorities, and by foreign powers and agencies. The course will focus on such topics as the meaning and reasons of underdevelopment; political and economic development; modernization; theories explaining underdevelopment such as dependency school, Marxist theories, liberal school; North-South gap; general characteristics of the developing countries; the challenges of the Third World development, etc.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT410 Human Rights</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course begins with an introduction to basic philosophies about human rights. We will address such questions as: What are human rights? Are human rights universal? Who is responsible for protecting human rights? We will then examine basic international and regional principles, instruments and institutions addressing human rights. We will look in depth at a limited number of specific 20th century human rights cases. Finally, attention will be paid to activism for human rights international and domestically.

    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT412 Public Administrative Law</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course is inaptly named, but tradition controls. Actually, other law school courses take up particular aspects of administrative law, i.e., the law produced by government agencies through their regulations and case decisions. Among those courses are Corporations, Environmental Law, Federal Income Tax, Labor Law, and Securities Regulation. The course named Administrative Law deals not with the substantive law of various agencies, but with the common process by which such law is produced and challenged.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT501 CIS & Regional Integration in Central Asia</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course provides an analyses of regional integration in Central Asia after the disintegration of URSS. This study includes mainly the study of CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States) as an organization which was founded by the post-soviet states and marked profoundly Central Asian countries as well as other members. The regional integration processes in Central Asia were also affected by the other actors: the world powers like USA and China. In this context, analysis of (Shanghai Cooperation Organization) is of vital importance to understand regional politics. SCO was built by the initiatives of China and Russia and the Central Asian countries to counterweight the USA presence in the region. The response of USA to this question: the concept of the Greater Central Asia will be included in this study.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT503 Central Asia & Caucasus in International Perspective</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course examines ethnic, religious, cultural, economic, and political factors contributing to the collapse of the Soviet Union and the emergence of new successor republics in Central Asia and the Caucasus. The efforts of these republics (Azerbaijan, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Kazakhstan, Kyrgystan, Tajlkistan) to achieve and sustain political and economic viability, while developing and strengthening national identities will also be studied.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT505 Russia in World Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course will focus on contemporary Russian politics and society, with secondary attention on other countries of the former Soviet Union. What was Soviet-type socialism, and how is its legacy shaping post-Soviet Russia? Where is Russia headed toward democracy as it is known in the West, a new form of authoritarianism, reversion to the old system, or something else? The social movements that swept Russia and the other Soviet republics during the Gorbachev period will be explored. We will devote most of the course to the Yeltsin and Putin periods and current problems of political change and upheaval. Contemporary Russian politics is a caldron of buccaneer entrepreneurs, high-flying mafiosi, liberal idealists, old communists, new fascists, and charismatics and demagogues of all types, and none of these will escape our attention. The topics to be investigated include the dilemmas of transition from a command economy to capitalism, struggles among emerging social interests and groups, the changing role of the military in society, crime and social disintegration, the rise of nationalism and the search for national identity, and ethnic conflict.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT507 Turkey in World Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course presents the development of the Turkish political system from the Ottoman period to the present. It surveys Turkish political life and institutions from a dynamic perspective, and the interaction of state, politics and society from a historical perspective. Topics covered: the history of the Turkish constitutional movement, the single-party period of the 1930s, multi-party politics since the 1940s, current issues in Turkish political life with special emphasis on secularism, civil-military relations, and problems of democracy. The objective of this course is to analyze the social and political structure of contemporary Turkey from a theoretical and historical perspective. Therefore it deals with some current issues and problems in Turkish political life such as problems of democracy, secularism and Islam, nationalism and identity, the military, civil society and new social movements, and citizenship.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT540 Nationalism & Minorities in International Perspective</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      The aim of this course is to apply theoretical approaches to nationalism to the post-Soviet context, illuminating the study of a region where any large-scale nationalist conflict would pose a serious threat to the political, economic and military stability of Europe. The course is not designed to give a 'Cook's Tour' of all the fifteen successor states. Rather, the core issues of nationalism and ethnic relations will be studies in each state in the light of the conceptual framework drawn up in the early classes. The course will be based in History and the Social Sciences. There is no language requirement, although additional reading lists can be supplied to any students who are competent in any of the East Slavonic languages. European national, ethnic, and religious minorities have for the past two hundred years been of fundamental importance to the ideology and decisionmaking in European multicultural and monocultural states. In modern Europe, minority issues are constantly debated and acted upon, both by majorities and minorities. Minority issues take up a central place in the public and intellectual debate, and also influence political decisionmaking among world leaders. Minority issues in Europe are closely connected to concepts of nationalism, identity, historical and geographical consciousness, language, cultural boundaries, stereotyping, national and international law, human rights, assimilation, and the concomitant scholarly analysis and classification of these phenomena.

    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>INT506 China in World Politics</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course is designed to survey major topics of the foreign policy of the People’s Republic of China (PRC). It begins with a brief introduction of a historical review of China’s role of the pre-modern world. The main body of the courses includes: (1) the development of Chinese foreign policy after the founding of the PRC, (2) China’s foreign policy toward Central Asia, (3), the domestic determinants and foreign policy decision-making in China, (4) current issues in and future of China’s foreign policy. The course aims to acquaint students with knowledge of China’s involvement in world affairs in historical and contemporary perspectives and train them with an analytical understanding of the dynamics of China’s foreign policy.
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="clear"></div>
</div>
<div class="course-cont">
  <div class="course">
    <span class="course-arrow">&raquo;</span> <div class="course-title"><h4>RSM509 Research Methods</h4></div>
    <div class="course-descr">
      This course, Research Methods, is designed for students who wish to gain an understanding of the limits and potentials of social science research, and for those who intend to research social phenomena scientifically. This course is intended to facilitate the student's awareness of the research process and their ability to conduct research in an ethical and thorough manner with appropriate research strategies. This course is an introduction to the methods employed in the practice of political science research. The two primary goals of the course are: (1) to provide new analytic tools that will help in the critical evaluation of a wide variety of social science material, and (2) to improve students' ability to pose and answer research questions on their own. The strengths and limitations of qualitative, quantitative, and formal methods will be considered.
    </div>
  </div>
